if they weren't distinct
you could just sort them
and then use 3-pointer
where your pointers are
left endpoint of [x - K], right endpoint of [x - k], current element
and maintain all elements between the first 2 pointers in a frequency counter (i.e. hashmap)
where you're counting what value they have at time i + 1
and then query is just checking hashmap
gives you O(NMlog M)

#include <bits/stdc++.h> using namespace std; typedef long long LL; #define A first #define B second #define SZ(x) int(x.size()) #define FR(i, a, b) for(int i=(a); i<(b); i++) #define FOR(i, n) FR(i, 0, n) int n; const int MAXN = 100100; int x[MAXN]; LL s[MAXN]; vector<pair<int, int> > lis[MAXN]; int ma[MAXN]; void Moo() { s[0] = 0; FOR(i, n) s[i + 1] = s[i] + LL(x[i]); FOR(i, n) { lis[i].clear(); lis[i].push_back(make_pair(0, 1)); ma[i] = 1; } FOR(i, n) { int j2 = i; for(int j1 = lis[i].size() - 1; j1 >= 0; --j1) { LL s1 = s[i + 1] - s[lis[i][j1].first]; int del = 1; while(j2 + del < n && s[j2 + del + 1] - s[i + 1] <= s1) { j2 += del; del *= 2; } while(del) { if(j2 + del < n && s[j2 + del + 1] - s[i + 1] <= s1) { j2 += del; } del /= 2; } int j3 = j2; int h_new = lis[i][j1].second + 1; while(j3 > i && h_new > ma[j3]) { ma[j3] = h_new; lis[j3].push_back(make_pair(i + 1, h_new)); j3--; } } } } int rec[MAXN]; int main() { scanf("%d", &n); FOR(i, n) scanf("%d", &x[i]); Moo(); FOR(i, n) rec[i] = lis[i][lis[i].size() - 1].second; int ans = max(ans, rec[n - 1]); for(int i = 0; i < n - 1 - i; ++i) swap(x[i], x[n - 1 - i]); Moo(); ans = max(ans, lis[n - 1][lis[n - 1].size() - 1].second); //combine FOR(i, n - 1) { ans = max(ans, lis[i][lis[i].size() - 1].second + rec[n - 2 - i]); } printf("%d\n", ans); return 0; }

Riolku 30-Jan-21 11:46 PM
aight
i have to write up this proof in like
a day
but
here goes
Let K > 2, and let A_i be our answer array
So A_1 is the number of times you pour into the first bucket
and since its a circle, let Ai = A\{i + N} (edited)
Now it should be pretty clear that we have equations to satisyf, namely
A{i - 1} + KA\{i} + A_{i + 1} = M
that is
for any bucket
the number of times we pour into it
times K
plus the number of times we pour into the side buckets
has to total to M
right?
ross_cleary 30-Jan-21 11:47 PM
Yes
Riolku 30-Jan-21 11:48 PM
let a = Ai, b = A\{i + 1}, c = A_{i + 2}, d = A_{i + 3} (convenience)
we have
a + bK + c = M b + cK + d = M
subtract
(a - b) + (b - c)K + (c - d) = 0
rearrange
(c - b) + (b - c)K + (a - d) = 0
(b - c)(K - 1) = (d - a)
now since K > 2, we have
(K - 1) > 1
so
(b - c)(K - 1) > (b - c)
and so (d - a) > (b - c)
rearrange
c + d > a + b
a + b < c + d
this should start raising some red flags
we now have
A_i + A_{i + 1} < A_{i + 2} + A_{i + 3}
now < is transitive, so in fact, we have
A_i + A_{i + 1} < A_{i + 2k} + A_{i + 2k + 1}
for any integer k
but this means we have
A_i + A_{i + 1} < A_{i + 2N} + A_{i + 2N + 1} = A_i + A_{i + 1}
a contradiction
i forgot to do setup properly earlier ree
(b - c)(K - 1) > (b - c)
this only holds if we have b != c
if b < c, we can just rearrange and flip (no loss of generality)
since we know that (edited)
(b - c)(K - 1) = (d - a)
and that assuming b != c leads to a contradiction
we must have b = c
so we have A_{i + 1} = A_{i + 2}
and so our answer array has the same values
